{# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   /heatmap — standalone full-tapestry interactive (v3)

   v3 iteration following JM feedback on v2: heatmap rendered only
   ~4 years wide (2010-2014) at real viewports because of an
   uncaught flex-chain bug; and the vertical space between the
   heatmap and the wealth-over-time chart (~700px of intermediate
   stat strip + section eyebrow + h2 + lede + §2 controls + chart
   label) was breaking the immersive interaction loop. Every cell
   click forced the user to scroll down to see the chart change,
   then scroll back up to click another cell.

   v3 redesign collapses all that intermediate space:

   1) THE PATTERN stat strip moves from BELOW the heatmap to ABOVE
      it, just under the hero. Acts as a takeaway summary headline
      for the page; doesn't separate the heatmap from the chart.

   2) "Explore a scenario" section eyebrow + h2 + lede is REMOVED.
      Was pure visual separator with no information value once the
      heatmap-to-chart relationship is made clear by adjacency.

   3) §2 calculator CONTROLS (mode toggle, presets, sliders, h3
      heading) are kept in the DOM (so bvsm.js's event bindings
      still wire up correctly) but hidden visually via CSS. The
      heatmap's own mode toggle (Bitcoin mode: Lump-sum / Weekly
      DCA) becomes the single mode control for both the heatmap
      AND the wealth-over-time chart. bvsm.js's wireHeatmapToggles
      now syncs heatmap mode → §2 mode on click, so the chart
      re-renders in the matching mode automatically.

   4) Chart sits immediately below the heatmap legend. Chart label
      moves from ABOVE the canvas to BELOW it (via CSS flex order),
      so nothing visual sits between the heatmap and the chart
      canvas itself.

   Net effect: heatmap → chart adjacency. On any reasonable desktop
   viewport, the user can see both the heatmap and the chart at
   once, click cells without scrolling, see the chart update in
   real time. The intended immersive feedback loop.

   Also fixed in v3: the heatmap.css overrides that were supposed
   to fit ~197 monthly columns into the container width weren't
   actually working because (a) .bvsm-heatmap-gridwrap has
   `flex: 0 0 auto` in bvsm.css, so the gridwrap stayed at content
   size regardless of the container; and (b) .bvsm-heatmap-cell has
   a hard-coded `width: 7px`, fighting the minmax(0, 1fr) grid
   tracks. heatmap.css now overrides both: gridwrap is
   `flex: 1 1 auto` and cells are `width: auto`.
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

<main class="heatmap-standalone">

    <section class="heatmap-hero">
        <h1>The <em>Bitcoin</em> Heatmap</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">
            Every monthly entry since 2010, every common holding horizon &mdash; bitcoin's outperformance against the S&amp;P 500 and the NASDAQ-100 across roughly 1,500 possible windows, in one grid.
        </p>
        <p class="heatmap-howto">
            Amber means bitcoin outperformed over that window; red means it lost. Intensity shows by how much. <strong>Click any cell to load that exact scenario into the chart below.</strong>
        </p>
    </section>

    <div class="bvsm-page">

        {# ═══ PATTERN STAT STRIP — moved ABOVE the heatmap ════════════
           bvsm.js's renderSidebar() populates this with title + 3
           bullet stats + foot label. heatmap.css restyles the
           container as a compact horizontal strip. Sitting between
           the hero and the heatmap, it acts as a takeaway summary
           that primes the user for the visual below — rather than
           the v2 placement which sat BETWEEN the heatmap and the
           chart, pushing the chart out of immediate view. #}
        <aside class="bvsm-heatmap-sidebar" id="bvsmHeatmapSidebar" aria-label="Pattern summary"></aside>

        {# ═══ HEATMAP COMPONENT — full canvas ═════════════════════════ #}
        <section class="heatmap-component">
            <div class="bvsm-heatmap-wrapper">
                <div class="bvsm-heatmap-controls">
                    <div class="bvsm-heatmap-control-group">
                        <span class="bvsm-heatmap-control-label">Bitcoin compared to:</span>
                        <button class="bvsm-heatmap-cmp-btn is-active" data-hm-cmp="sp500" type="button">S&amp;P 500 TR</button>
                        <button class="bvsm-heatmap-cmp-btn"           data-hm-cmp="ndq"   type="button">NASDAQ-100 TR</button>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bvsm-heatmap-control-group">
                        <span class="bvsm-heatmap-control-label">Bitcoin mode:</span>
                        <button class="bvsm-heatmap-mode-btn is-active" data-hm-mode="lump" type="button">Lump-sum</button>
                        <button class="bvsm-heatmap-mode-btn"           data-hm-mode="dca"  type="button">Weekly DCA</button>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bvsm-heatmap-control-group">
                        <span class="bvsm-heatmap-control-label">View:</span>
                        <button class="bvsm-heatmap-view-btn is-active" data-hm-view="window" type="button">Period return</button>
                        <button class="bvsm-heatmap-view-btn"           data-hm-view="hold"   type="button">Held to today</button>
                    </div>
                </div>

                {# Layout collapses to a single column on standalone
                   (the sidebar was moved out, above the wrapper).
                   .bvsm-heatmap-main becomes full width. #}
                <div class="bvsm-heatmap-layout">
                    <div class="bvsm-heatmap-main" data-chart-copy data-chart-capture="dom" data-chart-title="The Bitcoin outperformance heatmap" data-chart-filename="bitcoin-outperformance-heatmap.png">
                        <div class="bvsm-heatmap-scroll-container" id="bvsmHeatmapScroll">
                            <div class="bvsm-heatmap-sticky-left">
                                <div class="bvsm-heatmap-yaxis-title"><span>Holding period</span></div>
                                <div class="bvsm-heatmap-yaxis" id="bvsmHeatmapYaxis"></div>
                            </div>
                            <div class="bvsm-heatmap-gridwrap">
                                <div class="bvsm-heatmap-grid" id="bvsmHeatmapGrid"></div>
                                <div class="bvsm-heatmap-xaxis" id="bvsmHeatmapXaxis"></div>
                                <div class="bvsm-heatmap-xaxis-title">Entry month &rarr;</div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bvsm-heatmap-legend">
                            <div class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-scale">
                                <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="loss-deep">&lt;&#x2212;50%</span>
                                <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="loss">&#x2212;50% to &#x2212;10%</span>
                                <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="flat">&#x00B1;10%</span>
                                <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="win-mild">+10% to 2&times;</span>
                                <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="win-mid">2&times; to 5&times;</span>
                                <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="win-deep">&gt;5&times;</span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-note">Color = bitcoin&rsquo;s outperformance multiple over the comparator. Click any cell to load that scenario into the chart below. <strong>View toggle above:</strong> <em>Period return</em> reads each cell as the return over the cell&rsquo;s specific window — short windows can show red even when long-term holders did fine. <em>Held to today</em> reads each cell as the return from that entry date to today, for someone who held through — turning historical short-window dips orange once you account for the eventual recovery.</div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="bvsm-heatmap-tooltip" id="bvsmHeatmapTooltip" role="tooltip" aria-hidden="true"></div>
            </div>
        </section>

        {# ═══ CHART — immediately below the heatmap ═══════════════════
           Full §2 markup is included so bvsm.js's init() wires up the
